      "note_no": "53",
      "note": "Lit., \"is indeed wont to command [the doing of] evil\" - i.e., is filled with impulses which often conflict with what the mind regards as a moral good. This is obviously a reference to the statement in verse 24 above - \"she desired him, and he desired her; [and he would have succumbed,] had he not seen [in this temptation] an evidence of his Sustainer's truth\" - as well as to Joseph's prayer in verse 33, \"unless Thou turn away their guile from me, I might yet yield to their allure\". (See also note 23 above.) Joseph's stress on the weakness inherent in human nature is a sublime expression of humility on the part of one who himself had overcome that very weakness: for, as the sequence shows, he attributes his moral victory not to himself but solely to the grace and mercy of God."
